I'm not lying.  Just run CMD.EXE.  At the command prompt, enter:

cscript "%PROGRAMFILES%\Microsoft Office\Office14\ospp.vbs" /dstatus

This command tells if your copy of Office 2010 is permanent or 180 days.

What Zzerop is talking about with the MAK Keys thing is this:

Microsoft released MAK (Multiple Activation Key) Product Keys for certain Office 2010 BETA Products. It allows you to actually activate your BETA copy online until it is set to expire in October. 

However, people found out that they can use these same keys to activate Office 2010 RTM/Final online. Since there is no expiration on Office 2010 RTM/Final, it's a permanent activation.

What people don't understand, like Zzerop, is that Microsoft will not allow these MAK Keys to activate online past October. So, if he ever needs to reinstall Office 2010, he will not be able to unless he learns how to save the online activation information files for Office 2010. Even then, he can only use those activation information files on that same computer and thus he can't install Office 2010 on any other computer in the future with this method unless he already activated these other computers with MAK Keys and saved the files as well.

So, it's not a final solution unfortunately. However, if you all really want to know about MAK Keys and possibly get one, do a search on Google for "MAK Key Office 2010" and you might be able to find one. It's a lot better than these virus filled activators.

@softwarechecker,

I assume that you've completed the uninstall/install process.

You then must copy the "dat" files into the -CORRECT- folders.

You then run CMD.EXE as Administrator.

At the command prompt, you enter 2 commands:

cscript ?%PROGRAMFILES%\Microsoft Office\Office14\ospp.vbs? /inpkey:XXXXX-XXXXX-XXXXX-XXXXX-XXXXX

cscript ?%PROGRAMFILES%\Microsoft Office\Office14\ospp.vbs? /act


Your Office 2010 should be activated.  To check the status of activation, at the command prompt, enter

cscript ?%PROGRAMFILES%\Microsoft Office\Office14\ospp.vbs? / dstatus
